{"title_page": "David Shute", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2018}}\n{{for|the American professional ice hockey and roller hockey player|David Shute (ice hockey)}}\n'''David Shute''' is a British journalist, best known for his work at the [[BBC]].\n\n==Career==\nShute was educated at [[Brentwood School (England)|Brentwood School]] in [[Essex]]. While working on newspapers in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] he was auditioned by the BBC in [[Bristol]] and immediately signed on contract. He made a reputation for engaging in adventurous broadcasts such as [[deep sea diving]],<ref name=\"v3p\">{{cite web |title=Fun at the BBC |url=http://u3avalldelpop.com/newsletter_nov10.pdf |website=U3a News4u Vall del Pop |publisher=U3a News4u Vall del Pop |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref> riding on the back of a [[Royal Artillery]]<ref name=\"v3p\">{{cite web |title=Fun at the BBC |url=http://u3avalldelpop.com/newsletter_nov10.pdf |website=U3a News4u Vall del Pop |publisher=U3a News4u Vall del Pop |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref> motorcycle during a display and, while covering a story on the changing face of circus life, going on the [[flying trapeze]]. David Shute was the first person to broadcast live to the [[UK]] while travelling through the [[sound barrier]]. He is regularly on [[BBC Radio Four]]'s ''[[Today programme]]''.<ref name=\"v3p\">{{cite web |title=Fun at the BBC |url=http://u3avalldelpop.com/newsletter_nov10.pdf |website=U3a News4u Vall del Pop |publisher=U3a News4u Vall del Pop |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref> As a reporter he covered conflicts in [[Borneo]] and [[Sarawak]] which resulted in the Radio Four programme ''The Quiet Confrontation'', produced by [[Roy Hayward]]. He also covered the troubles in [[Aden]] and the [[Radfan]]. {{citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n\nHe was promoted to the post of Senior Talks Producer at the BBC's [[Pebble Mill]] studios.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Harper |first1=Patricia |title=Guilt Trip |date=2007 |publisher=Lulu |isbn=141166213X |pages=276}}</ref> There he built a reputation for mounting outside broadcasts. He maintained a productive association with the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at [[Stratford upon Avon]] and worked with actors including [[Ian Richardson]], [[Richard Pasco]] and [[Margaret Tyzack]]. He directed Richardson's memorable radio performance of [[Nevil Shute]]'s ''[[Requiem for a Wren]]'', which was featured as a ''[[Book at Bedtime]]''. He gave David Suchet his first broadcast job, reading a \"Morning Story\".\n\nOutside the BBC he wrote and produced ''Warwick Castle Mediaeval Banquet'', which ran for more than 17 years. He later founded a Production Company specialising in Video and Conference Production. {{citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n\n==Retirement==\nLiving in retirement in [[Spain]], Shute works as a lecturer on [[cruise ship]]s covering such topics as \"broadcasting\" and \"the musical theatre\", accompanied by recordings of his work as a reporter. Ashore he finds himself in demand as an after dinner speaker. {{citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.davidshute.co.uk David Shute's official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shute, David}}\n[[Category:British expatriates in Spain]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:British television producers]]\n[[Category:British radio producers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Brentwood, Essex]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=September 2018}}\n{{for|the American professional ice hockey and roller hockey player|David Shute (ice hockey)}}\n'''David Shute''' is a British journalist, best known for his work at the [[BBC]].\n\n==Career==\nShute was educated at [[Brentwood School (England)|Brentwood School]] in [[Essex]]. While working on newspapers in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] he was auditioned by the BBC in [[Bristol]] and immediately signed on contract. He made a reputation for engaging in adventurous broadcasts such as [[deep sea diving]],<ref name=\"v3p\">{{cite web |title=Fun at the BBC |url=http://u3avalldelpop.com/newsletter_nov10.pdf |website=U3a News4u Vall del Pop |publisher=U3a News4u Vall del Pop |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref> riding on the back of a [[Royal Artillery]]<ref name=\"v3p\">{{cite web |title=Fun at the BBC |url=http://u3avalldelpop.com/newsletter_nov10.pdf |website=U3a News4u Vall del Pop |publisher=U3a News4u Vall del Pop |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref> motorcycle during a display and, while covering a story on the changing face of circus life, going on the [[flying trapeze]]. David Shute was the first person to broadcast live to the [[UK]] while travelling through the [[sound barrier]]. He regularly on [[BBC Radio Four]]'s ''[[Today programme]]'' programme.<ref name=\"v3p\">{{cite web |title=Fun at the BBC |url=http://u3avalldelpop.com/newsletter_nov10.pdf |website=U3a News4u Vall del Pop |publisher=U3a News4u Vall del Pop |accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref> As a reporter he covered conflicts in [[Borneo]] and [[Sarawak]] which resulted in the Radio Four programme ''The Quiet Confrontation'', produced by [[Roy Hayward]]. He also covered the troubles in [[Aden]] and the [[Radfan]]. {{citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n\nHe was promoted to the post of Senior Talks Producer at the BBC's [[Pebble Mill]] studios.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Harper |first1=Patricia |title=Guilt Trip |date=2007 |publisher=Lulu |isbn=141166213X |pages=276}}</ref> There he built a reputation for mounting outside broadcasts. He maintained a productive association with the [[Royal Shakespeare Company]] at [[Stratford upon Avon]] and worked with actors including [[Ian Richardson]], [[Richard Pasco]] and [[Margaret Tyzack]]. He directed Richardson's memorable radio performance of [[Nevil Shute]]'s ''[[Requiem for a Wren]]'', which was featured as a ''[[Book at Bedtime]]''. He gave David Suchet his first broadcast job, reading a \"Morning Story\".\n\nOutside the BBC he wrote and produced ''Warwick Castle Mediaeval Banquet'', which ran for more than 17 years. He later founded a Production Company specialising in Video and Conference Production. {{citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n\n==Retirement==\nLiving in retirement in [[Spain]], Shute works as a lecturer on [[cruise ship]]s covering such topics as \"broadcasting\" and \"the musical theatre\", accompanied by recordings of his work as a reporter. Ashore he finds himself in demand as an after dinner speaker. {{citation needed|date=December 2009}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.davidshute.co.uk David Shute's official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shute, David}}\n[[Category:British expatriates in Spain]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:British television producers]]\n[[Category:British radio producers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Brentwood, Essex]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Copyedit, fixing duplicated words: programme", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Shute"}
{"title_page": "Friday Film House", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Friday Film House\n| logo             = Friday Film House Logo.png\n| caption          = \n| type             = [[Privately held company|Private]]<br>[[Film production]]<br>[[Film distribution]]\n| owner            = [[Vijay Babu]]\n| founder          = [[Vijay Babu]], [[Sandra Thomas]]\n| key_people       = \n| founded          = \n| location_city    = [[Trivandrum]]\n| location_country = [[India]]\n| subsid =<div>\n* Friday Film Experiments\n* Friday Tickets (Film Distribution)</div>\n| industry         = [[Film production]]<br>[[Film distribution]]\n| products         = Films\n| revenue          =  \n| operating_income = \n| website          = [https://www.fridayfilmhouse.com Friday Film House]\n}}\n\n'''Friday Film House''', is an Indian film production company based in the [[Malayalam]] film industry. It was founded by [[Vijay Babu]] and [[Sandra Thomas]].<ref name=\"Founder\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fridayfilmhouse.com/|title=Friday Film House|accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/movies/vijay-babus-friday-film-house-launches-yet-another-new-director-with-sullu/article29233558.ece|title=Vijay Babu\u2019s Friday Film House launches yet another new director with 'Sullu'|accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref> Though the company was established after the release of ''[[Friday (2012 film)|Friday]]'', the movie is considered as its first production venture. The Friday Film House won 7 of the Kerala State Film Awards in various fields in 2014. On January 3, 2017, the founders had a quarrel with each other in their office after which Sandra Thomas filed a case against Vijay Babu. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/actor-vijay-babu-accused-of-assaulting-producer-sandra-thomas-how-their-friendship-soured-3187136.html|title=Actor Vijay Babu accused of assaulting producer Sandra Thomas: How their friendship soured|accessdate=4 January 2017}}</ref> Later both declared that it was a misunderstanding and that Sandra had taken a break from the industry. Subsequently the stake of Sandra in the firm was excluded and the possession solely acquired by Vijay Babu.\n\n== Films ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| {{dagger|alt=Films that have not yet been released}}\n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Director\n!class=unsortable| Notes\n!class=unsortable| Ref.\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Friday (Malayalam film)|Friday]]'' || Production<br />Distribution || [[Lijin Jose]] || || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/friday-another-with-multi-narrative-aspect/259148-71-210.html|title=Friday: Another with multi narrative aspect}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Zachariayude Garbhinikal]]'' || Production || [[Aneesh Anwar]] || || <ref name=\"Zach\">{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/entertainment/mollywood/050619/friday-film-house-to-produce-gangs-of-bandadukka.html|title=Friday Film House to produce Gangs of Bandadukka|work=[[Deccan Chronicle]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Philips and the Monkey Pen]]'' || Production<br />Distribution || [[Rojin Thomas]]<br />Shanil Muhammed || Kerala State Film Award for Best Children's Film Director <br /> Kerala State Film Award for Best Child Artist - [[Sanoop Santhosh]] <br /> Kerala State Film Award for Best Children's Film <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nowrunning.com/movie/12271/malayalam/philips-and-the-monkey-pen/index.htm |title=Philips and the Monkey Pen Malayalam Movie - Preview, Trailers, Gallery, Review, Events, Synopsis |publisher=Nowrunning.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecinenews.com/2013/11/philips-and-monkey-pen-movie-review.html |title=What got special on'Philips & th